[49m[38;5;9m- 132     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m This is messier than it sounds. The "canonical source" varies by measure: HEDIS uses claims-and-supplemental-data with strict source-of-truth rules; the practice's quality dashboard may treat the EHR as canonical; the public-health immunization registry is canonical in some states for vaccines and not in others. The recommender's state machine has to know each measure's canonical source.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is messier than it sounds. The "canonical source" varies by measure: HEDIS uses claims-and-supplemental-data with strict source-of-truth rules; the practice's quality dashboard may treat the EHR as canonical; the public-health immunization registry is canonical in some states for vaccines and not in others. The recommender's state machine has to know each measure's canonical source.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Data Quality as a First-Class Signal
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The gap evaluation step produces a `data_quality_flag` per (patient, measure) that captures source-completeness assessment: values include `complete`, `sparse_history`, `multi_source_disagreement`, `recent_plan_change`, and `cross_provider_fragmentation`. This flag is not metadata. It is an input to every downstream stage:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The urgency scorer dampens confidence on non-`complete` cases (a confident urgency score on a patient whose data is fragmentary is overconfidence).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The visit-context ranker suppresses low-quality gaps from the in-visit agenda (surfacing a "gap" that might already be closed at another provider wastes limited visit time).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The async orchestrator routes low-quality cases to a verification-first pathway before any closure-specific outreach (call to confirm status before launching a reminder cascade).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The closure tracker tightens (or, for `cross_provider_fragmentation`, relaxes) the canonical-source rule.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The chase-team brief opens with verification framing when data quality is in doubt ("confirm whether patient has already had this screening elsewhere before proceeding with the gap-closure script").
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The "calling a patient about a colonoscopy they had last week" failure mode that the Honest Take warns about is exactly what `cross_provider_fragmentation` flags. Not gating downstream decisions on the data quality flag produces precisely that failure. A confidently "open" gap on a patient with `cross_provider_fragmentation` is a confidently wrong recommendation if the patient already had the procedure at a non-network provider.
